This is the standard workflow every developer follows daily.

Suppose:

* `main` has latest team code
* your branch = `login-feature`

---

# STEP 1 → Move to main branch

```bash id="vlk5o2"
git checkout main
```

Meaning:

```text id="x2j6hg"
Switch to main branch
```

---

# STEP 2 → Pull latest code from GitHub

```bash id="6v1qtf"
git pull origin main
```

Meaning:

```text id="ny2v3x"
Download latest main branch updates from GitHub
```

Now your local `main` is updated.

---

# STEP 3 → Move back to your branch

```bash id="w3m9pr"
git checkout login-feature
```

Now you are back in your branch.

---

# STEP 4 → Bring latest main code into your branch

```bash id="rntjlwm"
git merge main
```

Meaning:

```text id="0cz6iy"
Merge updated main branch code into my branch
```

Now your branch contains:

* latest main updates
* your own feature code

---

# COMPLETE FLOW

```bash id="1t6epr"
git checkout main

git pull origin main

git checkout login-feature

git merge main
```

---

# Real Example

Suppose:

* Person A added login page to main
* You are working on billing feature

Before continuing your work:

```bash id="6g0rjg"
git checkout main
git pull origin main
git checkout billing-feature
git merge main
```

Now your billing branch also gets:

* login feature updates

---

# Why this is important

Without this:

* your branch becomes old
* merge conflicts increase
* code breaks later

---

# Simple Visualization

Before merge:

```text id="2prq77"
main → login feature

billing-feature → old code
```

After:

```bash id="r1f0rf"
git merge main
```

Now:

```text id="9ecmly"
billing-feature → old code + login feature
```

---

# Small Important Tip

Sometimes instead of:

```bash id="2xjlwm"
git merge main
```

companies use:

```bash id="kbq6he"
git rebase main
```

But learn `merge` first.
It is easier and safer for beginners.


